\par \pard\plain \s98{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\sb0\sa120\cf0\kerning1\hich\af0\langfe2052\dbch\af0\loch\f0\fs24\lang7177{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
The test as to the existence of\~   \'91necessary implication\'92 was set out in }{\b\ab\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Rennie NO v Gordon & Another NNO }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
1998(1) SA (A) at 22 F as follows: \'91the implication is a necessary one in the sense that without it effect cannot be given to the statute as it stands\'92 In the present case, the reading suggested by first respondent would render the Tribunal powerless to prevent a violation of the Act.\~   In certain cases the conduct could be penalized later in terms of the divestiture provision, S. 60, but in others a violating party would be able to win a war of position with impunity.\~   In my view, the reading of the Tribunal\'92s powers as set out in }{\b\ab\rtlch \ltrch\loch
Seagram}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
\'92}{\b\ab\rtlch \ltrch\loch
s }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
case}{\b\ab\rtlch \ltrch\loch
, supra }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch
